{{use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} {{Infobox cricket tournament | name = 2021 Women's Cricket World Cup | image = | imagesize = | caption = | administrator = [[International Cricket Council]] | cricket format = [[One-Day International]] | tournament format = [[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]] and [[Single-elimination tournament|Knockout]] | host = {{flagicon|NZL}} [[New Zealand]] | fromdate = | todate = | champions = | runner up = | count = | participants = 8 | matches = | drs = | venues = | player of the series = | most runs = | most wickets = | website = [https://www.icc-cricket.com/womens-world-cup/ Official site] | previous_year = 2017 | previous_tournament = 2017 Women's Cricket World Cup | next_year = | next_tournament = }}
The '''2021 ICC Women's Cricket World Cup''' will be the twelfth edition of the [[Women's Cricket World Cup]] and is scheduled to be held in [[New Zealand]].<ref name="ICC-Oct17">{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/489022 |title=Women's cricket breaks new grounds |accessdate=9 October 2017 |work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]] have qualified automatically as hosts, and will be joined by three more teams from the ongoing [[2017–20 ICC Women's Championship]].<ref name="3+NZ">{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/785582 |title=England move to third position after 2–1 series win over New Zealand |accessdate=14 July 2018 |work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> The top four teams from a ten-team qualifier will also play in this edition of the Women's World Cup.<ref name="ICC-Oct17"/>
