[[File:Hastings Racecourse Track.jpg|thumb|250px|Hastings Racecourse]]
'''Hastings Racecourse''' is a [[horse racing]] facility at [[Hastings Park]] four miles from downtown [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Originally called East Park, it opened for business in 1889, making it Vancouver’s longest continuously used professional sports facility. The racing operation is currently a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Great Canadian Gaming]] Corporation who acquired the lease of the city-owned track in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/20/sports/canadian-racetrack-home-to-derby-winning-jockey-struggling-for-survival.html |title=Winning Jockey Came From a Struggling Track |date=May 19, 2012 |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |author=Bob Mackin}}</ref>
The track was originally known as Exhibition Park Race Track <ref>{{cite web|url=https://searcharchives.vancouver.ca/horse-racing-at-exhibition-park-race-track |title=Horse Racing at Exhibition Park Race Track |publisher=City of Vancouver Archives Item : CVA 180-3864 |date=1972-00-00 |accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref> but has always been referred to by the public and the media as Exhibition Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalpost.com/m/bower+collection+support+jockeys+hastings+racecourse/10077179/story.html |title=Bower collection to support jockeys at Hastings Racecourse |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=2014-07-30 |accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref> July 1, 1939, marked the first time [[Thoroughbred racing]] used an electric [[starting gate]], the invention of [[Texas|Texan]] [[Clay Puett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1930s/drf1939071401/drf1939071401_21_10 |title=Clay Puett Gate Makes Hit: New Starting Device, Closed Fore and Aft, Works to Perfection at Canadian |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1939-07-14|accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref>
On the first Monday in August, a public holiday, the track hosts BC Cup Day that features a series of six races for top [[Thoroughbred]]s in various classes. In September, the two most important races for three-year-olds in British Columbia, the [[British Columbia Oaks]] and the [[British Columbia Derby]], are run at Hastings Racecourse. Major races include:
'''[[Graded stakes race|Grade 3]]:''' * [[Lieutenant Governors Stakes]] * [[British Columbia Derby]] * [[British Columbia Premier's Handicap]] * Ballerina Stakes
'''Ungraded stakes:''' * [[British Columbia Oaks]] * [[Fantasy Stakes (Canada)|Fantasy Stakes]] * [[Ascot Graduation Stakes]]
On May 18, 2011 it was reported that the course could close at the end of its 2012 lease due to low profits from wagering revenue and slots as well as difficulty reaching an agreeable new lease with the city. A decision by Great Canadian had to be made by October 31 of that year.<ref name=am>[http://www.news1130.com/news/local/article/199670--hastings-racecourse-could-close Hastings Racecourse could close - News1130]</ref> The result of those negotiations was that the track remain open and running.
In 2012, Hastings Racecourse made international headlines when little-known Mexican-born jockey [[Mario Gutierrez (jockey)|Mario Gutierrez]] (who had emigrated to Canada in 2006 and begun riding at Hastings, winning the track's riding titles in 2007 and 2008), won the [[Santa Anita Derby]], the [[Kentucky Derby]] and the [[Preakness Stakes]] aboard [[I'll Have Another]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/Hastings+star+jockey+ready+roses+Kentucky+Derby/6555655/story.html |title=Mario Gutierrez takes unlikely path from poverty to Kentucky Derby win via east Vancouver racecourse |date=May 5, 2012 |publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]] |author=Yvonne Zacharias}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://vancouversun.com/sports/Mario+Gutierrez+Have+Another+wins+137th+Preakness+Stakes/6650633/story.htmll |title=Mario Gutierrez, I’ll Have Another wins 137th Preakness Stakes |date=May 19, 2012 |publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]] |author=Cam Tucker}}</ref> ==References== {{Reflist}}
