{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}} {{Use Australian English|date=December 2012}} [[File:Rottnest-Channel-Swim-start-2004.jpg|thumb|350px|The start of one wave of the Rottnest Channel Swim, 2004]] The '''Rottnest Channel Swim''' is an annual [[open water swimming]] event from [[Cottesloe, Western Australia|Cottesloe Beach]] through [[Gage Roads]] to [[Rottnest Island]], off the coast of [[Western Australia]], near [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]]. The distance is approximately 20 kilometres and it is one of the largest open-water swimming events in the world, with 2400 swimmers participating in the 2015 event.<ref name= new>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-11-12/port-to-pub-new-rottnest-swim-planned-for-2016/6935266 2016 Port to Pub: New Rottnest swim planned to meet demand for gruelling ocean crossing event]</ref>
It is held in February each year and is open to solo swimmers and teams of two or four. A second event, Champions of the Channel for elite swimmers, was introduced in 2016.<ref>[http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/western-australia/siblings-ben-and-jenna-freeman-making-wakes-ahead-of-rottnest-channel-swims-inaugural-champions-of-the-channel-race/news-story/9f6a9b5e1b01bdf9bc50955097b75d86 Siblings Ben and Jenna Freeman making waves ahead of Rottnest Channel Swim’s inaugural Champions of the Channel race]</ref>
==History== When Rottnest Island was used as a prison it was rumoured that some of the prisoners swam back to the mainland, although there is no proof that any did. However some may have crossed by resting on [[Carnac Island|Carnac]] and [[Garden Island (Western Australia)|Garden Islands]]. The first documented crossing by a swimmer was Gerd Von Dincklage-Schulinburg, on 24 January 1956. This led the Weekend Mail newspaper to hold the first organised race to the island in March later that year, which was completed by four participants.<ref name= history>[http://rottnestchannelswimassociation.com.au/history/history-ofrcs/ History of the Rottnest Channel Swim]</ref> The first woman to swim to the island was Lesley Cherriman on 13 April 1969.<ref>[http://www.users.bigpond.net.au/timtucak/voigt19.htm Regarding Schulinburg, Voigt, and Cherriman]</ref> The youngest swimmer to compete was [[Kutraleeswaran]] from [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]], who completed the swim at the age of 13 in 1994.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/sports/2005/oct/06spec.htm Why Kutraleeswaran stopped swimming]</ref>
Despite the modest success of the 1956 event, another organised race to the island would not be held until February 23, 1991, with sixteen solo swimmers and seven teams competing. The success of the swim lead it to it becoming an annual event.<ref name= history/> Due to the overwhelming popularity of the race, a ballot has been held since 2006 to limit the number of participants in the competition.<ref name= new/>
